SIMPLE: sedition
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sedition
<hw>Se*di"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>sedicioun</ets>, OF. <ets>sedition</ets>, F.
<ets>s⟦eacute⟧dition</ets>, fr. L. <ets>seditio</ets>, originally, a
going aside; hence, an insurrectionary separation; pref. <ets>se-</ets>,
<ets>sed-</ets>, aside + <ets>itio</ets> a going, fr. <ets>ire</ets>,
<ets>itum</ets>, to go. Cf. <er>Issue</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
raising of commotion in a state, not amounting to insurrection; conduct
tending to treason, but without an overt act; excitement of discontent
against the government, or of resistance to lawful authority.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In soothing them, we nourish 'gainst our senate⟦br⟧
The cockle of rebellion, insolence, <qex>sedition</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Noisy demagogues who had been accused of <qex>sedition</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Dissension; division; schism.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now the works of the flesh are manifest, . . . emulations, wrath,
strife, <qex>seditions</qex>, heresies.</q> <rj><qau>Gal. v. 19,
20.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Insurrection; tumult; uproar; riot; rebellion;
revolt. See <er>Insurrection</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Seditionary</ent>⟦br⟧
